<div class="recipe">
<p>This traditional Australian/New Zealand (depending on who you ask, we won't get into that discussion) dessert gives an experience unlike a lot of other desserts you have tried. The textural difference between the crispy meringue and smooth cream is just fantastic. And when cream has been sitting on top for a few minutes, it starts to soften the merignue below it, creating something that will remind you of a marshmallow. The tangy fresh fruit on top juxtaposes the sweetnees below it perfectly, creating a mouthwatering experience that will keep you coming back for more.</p>
<p>One of the best parts about this dessert is how far the ingredients stretch. Most of the volume of this dessert comes from the eggs in the form of the pastry cream and meringue. Just 3 eggs will create a dessert the size of a baking sheet.</p>
<p>This dessert if perfect for those warm summer nights where you want a satisfying, sweet treat without bogging yourself down with a large piece of pie or cake. Because a lot of this dessert is just air, it's surprisingly low-calorie for how great it tastes.</p>
<p>This dish requires you to make meringue, which is infamous for being finnicky. To start, having an electric beater will make this significantly easier. Second, and perhaps most important, you need to be using a very clean bowl to whisk the eggs in. When we say clean, we mean <i>clean</i>. Any oily residue will deflate your lovely foam. Having some yolk from the egg in there will also cause the same effect.</i></p>
<p>This recipe uses 3 eggs, which will create a large dessert. We have found that 1 egg per person will leave everyone with a very sizeable portion, or a light portion for 2 people. The quantities are easily divisible by 3 to get the base recipe per person, for you to scale as you desire.</p>
<p>It is best to make this dessert the night before you plan on serving it. The meringue is best when it has a chance to dry out in the oven all night. The meringue also only uses the egg whites, while the pastry cream uses only the egg yolks. So, save the yolks for that. The cream can be stored overnight with plastic wrap pressed firmly into the top to prevent it from drying out.</p>
