<div class="ingredients">
    <h3><strong>Ingredients</strong></h3>
    <strong>Meringue:</strong>
    <ul>
        <li>3 egg whites</li>
        <li>150g powdered sugar</li>
        <li>1 1/2 teaspoon lemon juice (or cream of tartar)</li>
        <li>1 1/2 teaspoon cornstarch</li>
        <li>salt, to taste</li>
    </ul>
    <strong>Pastry Cream:</strong>
    <ul>
        <li>3 egg yolks</li>
        <li>3 tablespoons sugar</li>
        <li>3 teaspoons cornstarch</li>
        <li>9 tablespoons milk</li>
        <li>3 tablespoons butter</li>
        <li>vanilla, to taste</li>
    </ul>
    <h3><strong>Directions</strong></h3>
    <strong>Meringue (make the night before):</strong>
    <ol>
        <li>Preheat the oven to 350F.</li>
        <li>Whisk the egg whites with an electric beater until soft peaks form. Which in the powdered sugar, no more than few tabelspoons at a time, until stiff peaks form - this may take over 10 minutes. Beat in the cornstarch and lemon juice until smooth.</li>
        <li>Dump the meringue onto a parchment lined baking sheet into a thick, round, cake-like shape. Try to give it a bit of a crust so it can contain the pastry cream later.</li>
        <li>Put it in the oven, then drop the temperature to 215F. Bake for 90 minutes, then turn off the oven but do not remove the meringue from the oven. Let it sit in there for as long as possible, but ideally overnight. We are trying to dehydrate it as much as possible here.</li>
    </ol>
    <strong>Pastry Cream:</strong>
    <ol>
        <li>Whisk the yolks with the sugar and cornstarch until smooth.</li>
        <li>In a medium saucepan, bring the milk to a simmer over medium-low heat. Slowly pour some of the milk into the egg mixture while stirring constantly. This will temper the eggs.</li>
        <li>With the eggs tempered, transfer everything back into the saucepan and bring it back up to a simmer, making sure to whisk constantly. When the cornstarch begins to gel, remove from the heat and stir until everything is smooth.</li>
        <li>Drop in the cold butter chunks and slowly whisk them in. You may need to put the mixture back on the heat if the butter is not melting. Once the butter is incorporated, whisk in the vanilla and extra salt if you want it.</li>
        <li>Transfer to a bowl, covered, and let it sit in the fridge until ready to top the meringue. Save the topping for the absolute last possible moment to preserve the textural contrast.</li>
        <li>Top with any fruits you wish, but tangy fruits work best, like raspberries, blackberries, etc. Enjoy!</li>
    </ol>
</div>
